Un jour, lors d'un voyage à Londres, les six jeunes femmes se rendent compte qu'elles en ont marre d'aller sur les applications de rencontre pour tenter de trouver l'âme sœur.

La bande de trentenaires célibataires a alors une idée lumineuse : monter un projet de rencontres idéales. L'idée est d'organiser des évènements dans des bars lyonnais dans un premier temps, et pourquoi pas dans toute la France, plus tard. Des soirées qu'elles souhaitent décontractées et conviviales, loin des speed-datings souvent embarrassants, comme l'explique Nina :

"Séduire quelqu'un qui ne nous plaît pas forcément, cela ne nous intéressait pas. Dans une soirée, on veut parler avec certaines personnes et on ne veut pas que l'on nous impose des gens comme lors des speed-datings. On a donc créé autre chose."


Rapidement, le projet se concrétise. Le premier évènement a lieu en décembre 2022 et le succès est au rendez-vous, puisqu'il y avait 25 femmes et 25 hommes. Parmi les critères : avoir entre 27 et 40 ans, être célibataire et chercher une relation sérieuse. Pour favoriser les échanges, Chloé et ses amies avaient prévu quelques animations :

"Lors de leur arrivée à la soirée, les participants prenaient un badge avec un nom fictif, que ce soit de superhéros ou de personnages de films, et cela détendait tout le monde. Parmi les autres idées proposées, ils devaient écrire sur une étiquette trois mots qui les définissaient."

posts.com:
My wife is north korean

Rather, she's koryo-saram, which are north koreans (before the north/south distinction existed) that migrated to far east russia in ~1880. Then they achieved great success in USSR, ranking first among other nations in the number of medals for hard work and labour. However after the japanese occupation of korea, stalin thought of them as spies, and deported all of them to uzbekistan and kazakhstan in trains that were meant to be used for livestock. They embarked them in a literal desert, many of them died, but they succeeded in recreating an enormous agricultural system, which later got praised once again. In post-USSR time there were many notable koryo-saram, such as Viktor Tsoi, who were also very influential on the russian culture
They lost their unique north korean dialect, which is no longer understood by neither south koreans, nor north koreans. After getting deported to uzbekistan and kazakhstan, they tried to revive their language, but stalin cancelled all those projects (opening schools, theatres, etc). Nowadays the only people who speak it fluently are over 90 years old, and the rest, the younger the more, are russified. My wife doesn't speak a word of it unfortunately.
They have many unique words for food as well as the recipes that were adapted to be affordable and accessible in USSR, for example kimchi is called chimchi, and is made using the ingredients available in russia and kazakhstan (however the cabbage and gochu(jang) were imported so it tastes similar, but not the same as SK kimchi). My wife is a Koryo-saram, which is a group of North Koreans who migrated to far eastern Russia in the late 1800s. They were very successful in the USSR and earned many medals for hard work and labor. However, after the Japanese occupation of Korea, Stalin accused them of being spies and deported them to Uzbekistan and Kazakhstan in trains meant for livestock. Many of them died in the desert, but they were able to recreate a successful agricultural system which was later praised. In the post-USSR era, there were many notable Koryo-saram, such as Viktor Tsoi, who also had a significant impact on Russian culture.

The Koryo-saram lost their unique North Korean dialect and it is no longer understood by either South Koreans or North Koreans. After being deported to Uzbekistan and Kazakhstan, they attempted to revive their language, but Stalin canceled these projects, including the opening of schools and theaters. Nowadays, only people over 90 years old can speak the dialect fluently, while younger generations are more Russified. My wife does not speak a word of it.

The Koryo-saram also have unique words for food and adapted recipes to make them more affordable and accessible in the USSR. For example, their version of kimchi, called chimchi, is made using ingredients available in Russia and Kazakhstan (though the cabbage and gochu [jang] are imported so it tastes similar but not the same as South Korean kimchi). They also have different names for certain foods, such as puktai which is called doenjang-jjigae in South Korea.

In terms of appearance, the Koryo-saram look quite different from modern South and North Koreans. My wife's father, for example, looks like a top tier actor from South Korean dramas, but without surgeries or makeup. My wife herself also looks like she belongs in the top 1% in Korea, China, or Japan, but she says that she looks average among other Koryo-saram.

Usually you'd drop the Ehe-, since it's more or less obvious. Your "woman" is the same thing as your wife.
>Meine Eltern haben sich vor dreißig Jahren verheiratet.
-> sind seit 30 Jahren verheiratet.
or, more awkward, but closer to the challenge
-> haben vor 30 Jahren geheiratet.

>Gleichgeschlechtliche Ehe ist jüngst in Kuba gesetzlich geworden.
jüngst -> vor Kurzem
gesetzlich -> legal
I'd also do some reordering. If "Gleichgeschlechtliche Ehe" is A, "vor kurzem" is B, and "in Kuba" is C, I'd do one of ACB, CAB, or CBA.
>Was mir gehört, gehört dir auch und umgekehrt.
-> gehört auch dir
You can also say
-> Was mein(s) ist, ist (auch) dein(s).
Leaving off the s makes it more poetic, but the challenge is kinda poetic, so whatever.
>Einige Leute finden Eheschließung veraltet zu sein, aber ich bin damit nicht einverstanden.
-> Einige Leute finden/meinen/denken, die Ehe sei veraltet, aber ich bin anderer Meinung.
desu, you could keep your first part, just cutting off "zu sein". It's perfectly fine to say "Subject finden Object Adjective"
mit etw. nicht einberstanden sein = not being OK with something. The way you wrote it, it sounds like you are disagreeing not with the opinion, but with the fact that the people have the opinion at all.
>Mein guter Freund hat sich während der Covid Pandemie mit seiner Fiancée verheiratet, weshalb die Hochzeit wurde bei Zoom durchgeführt.
-> Mein guter Freund hat seine Verlobte während der Coronapandemie (or just: während Corona) geheiratet, weshalb seine Hochzeit über Zoom durchgeführt wurde.
Bei Zoom sounds like it was at the Zoom office.

>>176094188
Non-rhotic American accents are at least somewhat stigmatized. There was a famous linguistic experiment decades ago demonstrating this: Researchers went to three department stores in New York City. One department store was working class, one was middle class, and one was upper class. The researchers asked the store attendants where a certain item was, knowing that the item was on the fourth floor. When the attendants responded, the ones at the working class store mostly said "fourth floor" with a non-rhotic accent, the ones at the upper class store used a rhotic accent, and the ones at the middle class store used both about evenly. What's really interesting is that when the researchers said "What did you say?" to get the attendants to repeat themselves, the working class and upper class attendants used the same accents as before, but the middle class attendants largely switched to a rhotic accent, suggesting that the middle class is more conscious of how their accents might be stigmatized.

>>176092824
both are fine sentences, but I think the former would be mainly restricted to formal writing. colloquially you'd want to elide the second 'ich', and perhaps also get rid of the subclause, so your instinct makes sense.
Ich lese, während ich esse. - I read while I eat. / I'm reading while I'm eating.
Ich lese beim Essen. / Ich lese während [des Essen / {colloq} dem Essen]. - [I read / I'm reading] while eating. / [I read / I'm reading] during the meal.
another way:
Ich lese und esse dabei. - I read and eat [meanwhile / during it]. / I'm reading and eating meanwhile.
>>176094400
it's correct. the reflexive sense isn't marked as old-fashioned or archaic anywhere in DWDS/Duden/Wiktionary, but it certainly doesn't seem as common anymore. you could say it's stuffy. so personally I'd always use 'heiraten' without the reflexive pronoun.
>Sie haben sich verheiratet. -> Sie haben geheiratet.
the main usage of this verb is in past participle ('verheiratet' - 'married'), i.e. as an adjective.
the last meaning says 'archaic' but it's really just the practice that's archaic in the West I'd say. e.g. if you're talking about arranged marriage in India, this would be fine:
>Er hat seine Tochter verheiratet. - He('s) married off his daughter.

By taking a ferry from Civitavecchia near Rome. I already tried back in April for the first time with a boat from Palermo but was denied entry because I lacked a so-called "hotel voucher". Had to board the next ferry back to Italy.

Tunisia's roads are surprisingly good, not much worse than Italy's. Tunisia is a shit hole of course but it's still one of the most developed countries on the African continent for what it's worth.
Roads on Google maps starting with P are very safe, those starting with a C are more risky but still generally okay to cycle on.

The fans understands this stuff; they have the intellectual capacity to truly appreciate the depths of North African village borders, to realise that they're not just extremely important - they say something deep about FLAGS.
As a consequence people who dislike Tunisian municipality flags truly ARE idiots - of course they wouldn't appreciate, for instance, the intricacies of the relationship between the newly formed Zaafrana-Dir Kef municipality, the Kef East delegation (which Zaafrana-Dir Kef is part of, by the way) and Kef proper, which itself is a cryptic reference to the fifth verse of the ninth surah of the Quran. I'm smirking right now just imagining one of those addlepated simpletons scratching their heads in confusion as Ovodda's genius wit unfolds itself in the github repository.
